Does multiple companies involved in the process of TV show making benefit the popularity of a TV show?

Christina Lyu & Sicong Li (using Github1)

4/26/2018

On October 30, 2017, after Kevin Spacey, one of the main casts, was accused by actor Anthony Rapp of making a sexual advance toward him, Netflix announced that the sixth season would be the final season of House of Cards. Originally released in 2013, House of Cards is an American political thriller television series with an average rating of 8.9/10 on IMBD. Although it is marked as Netflix original series, after looking through the production details of it, we found that it gives credits to multiple production companies, including Trigger Street Productions, which produced well-known films like Fifty Shades of Grey and The Social Network in previous years. [Problem Statement] Therefore, we are interested in investigating the relationship between the popularity of TV shows and the number of its production companies: do well-known TV shows are always produced by multiple production companies? If so, what are the underlying explanations for this phenomenon?

## [1] "MySQLConnection"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "RMySQL"
#The TV shows and the production companies with highest reviews ranked by year with at least 100,000 votes
#used four tables in imdb: movie_info_idx, title, movie_company, company_name
#used index column by using movie_info_idx
tv_rank <- db %>%
  dbGetQuery("SELECT distinct t.id, t.title, t.production_year, n.name,
  mi1.info AS votes, mi2.info AS rating
FROM title t
JOIN movie_info_idx AS mi1 ON mi1.movie_id = t.id
JOIN movie_info_idx AS mi2 ON mi2.movie_id = t.id
join movie_companies as c on c.movie_id = t.id
join company_name as n on n.id = c.company_id
WHERE t.kind_id = 2
#use index column
  AND mi1.info_type_id = 100
  AND mi2.info_type_id = 101
  AND mi1.info > 100000
ORDER BY t.production_year desc;")
tv_rank

Firstly, we wanted to analyze ratings among TV shows with at least 100,000 votes on IMDB. After a first glance, we figured out an interesting pattern that it seemed that all of the TV shows that are shown in our table have multiple rows with the same TV title, which means that they have multiple production companies. Since our table is too large to confirm our guess by looking through it, we created another table that counts the number of production companies of each of the TV shows.

#TV shows and how many companies were involved in the production in the TV shows with over 100,000 votes
#used four tables: title, movie_info_idx, movie_companies, company_name
#used index column: movie_info_index, and movie_company.company_id column to join it with company_name.id
tv_company <- db %>%
  dbGetQuery("SELECT title, count(distinct name) as companies, avg(mi1.info) as avg_votes, avg(mi2.info) as avg_rating, production_year
FROM title t
JOIN movie_info_idx AS mi1 ON mi1.movie_id = t.id
JOIN movie_info_idx AS mi2 ON mi2.movie_id = t.id
JOIN movie_companies as c on c.movie_id = t.id
JOIN company_name as n on n.id = c.company_id
WHERE t.kind_id = 2
  AND mi1.info_type_id = 100
  AND mi2.info_type_id = 101
  AND mi1.info > 100000
GROUP BY title, production_year
ORDER by production_year desc, avg_rating desc")
tv_company

The result, not surprisingly, is consistent with our guess that all of the TV shows with over 100,000 votes are produced by multiple companies. Therefore, we are curious about why a TV show with over 100,000 votes, which indicates that many people have watched that show, gives credits to multiple companies.

We came up with several possible explanations. Essentially, multiple roles are involved in the production of a TV shows. A distributor or a distribution company, for example, promises the network they will guarantee the episode and at times deficit finance the shows and is responsible for marketing the TV shows. In exchange, they own the rights to the show and can monetize it after its initial run. Distributors can be different in different countries, and even be different in the same country but for different platforms. Take 13 Reasons Why as an example, while Netflix is the distributor of video and on the internet in the US in 2017, Viacom owns the right to all media now. A TV show also gives credit to its IP owner: toy companies such as Mattel and Lego, comic book companies such as Marvel as the sceneries of the show are mainly based on their original stories.

Secondly, companies may choose to collaborate with other firms to minimize risks. As nobody wants to take a huge gamble by himself, instead of making big bets on high-budget franchise plays, production companies collaborate with other companies to lower the risk. A smaller indie production company may have a good idea, but it needs to seek for financial support to put its idea on screen. In this way, the risk of losing is distributed to several companies, and small to median production companies wont worry that a single investment failure will lead to bankrupt.

Another reason for this phenomenon is that many producers, stars, and writers have their studios through which they create and make a show. An example will be Brad Pitt and his production company, Plan-B Entertainment, which won the 86th a best-picture Oscar for 12 Years a Slave. Those people wont sign on to a show unless their production companies are hired. Thats a way to shield some of their payments from taxation, as the money is technically going to the production company, not themselves.

To confirm our guess, we also created a table that counts the number of TV shows that are less popular (have less than 100 votes on IMDB) and the number of production companies that are given credit to.

#TV shows and how many companies were involved in the production for shows that are not popular
tv_lesspop <- db %>%
  dbGetQuery("SELECT title, count(distinct name) as companies, avg(mi1.info) as avg_votes, production_year
FROM title t
JOIN movie_info_idx AS mi1 ON mi1.movie_id = t.id
JOIN movie_companies as c on c.movie_id = t.id
JOIN company_name as n on n.id = c.company_id
WHERE t.kind_id = 2
  AND mi1.info_type_id = 100
  AND mi1.info < 100
GROUP BY title, production_year
ORDER by production_year desc")
tv_lesspop

The result verifies our idea as most of the TV shows have only 1 or 2 production companies, indicated in the companies column.

#TV shows and how many companies were involved in the production for shows that are not popular
tv <- db %>%
  dbGetQuery("SELECT title, count(distinct name) as companies, avg(mi2.info) as avg_rating, production_year
FROM title t
JOIN movie_info_idx as mi2 ON mi2.movie_id = t.id
JOIN movie_companies as c on c.movie_id = t.id
JOIN company_name as n on n.id = c.company_id
WHERE t.kind_id = 2
  AND mi2.info_type_id = 101
GROUP BY title")
tv_company %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = avg_rating, x = companies, color = production_year)) + 
  geom_jitter() + 
  scale_colour_gradientn(colours = terrain.colors(10)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  ggtitle("relationship between the number of shows a company produces and their average rating") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 10)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

tv_level <- 
  tv %>%
  mutate(level = ifelse(avg_rating > 7.5, "high", ifelse(avg_rating < 5, "low", "median")))

tv_level %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = companies, fill = level)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0, 50)) + 
  ggtitle("Number of TV Shows vs Number of Companies Involved with Rating Level")

tv_level %>%
  filter(companies > 7) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = companies, fill = level)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(5, 20)) + 
  ggtitle("ZoomIn: #TV shows vs #Companies > 7 with Rating Level")

tv_level %>%
  filter(companies > 15) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = companies, fill = level)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(10, 100)) + 
  ggtitle("ZoomIn: #TV Shows vs #Companies > 15 with Rating Level")

To get a better understanding, we created several graphs to show patterns. For the first graph, we found that for TV shows with more than 100,000 votes in IMDb, at least three companies are involved in the production. Ratings of shows that were produced around 1990 are all above 8.5. It makes sense because in the old times, there was not so many ways to promote a show. People tried to make the shows with high qualities to get the viewers talk about it and increase the viewing party.

We also made a histogram to interpret the distribution of the number of companies involved in the production of a TV show. We plotted three levels of rating on the graph. Those with more than 7.5 scores are in the level of high, 5-7.5 are in the median, and smaller than 5 are in the low level. We found that over 80 percent of TV shows are produced by no more than 5 companies, but there are also around 10% of them have very low rating. For those with more than 5 companies involved, we can see that the percentage of low rating movies is gradually reduced as the number increases, and becomes unnoticable at the end, as companies will be more cautious about selecting scripts and choosing actors. Also music, special effects, and sounds can be improved a lot with more companies involved in, providing larger budgets.

#the percent of top tv shows
top <- 
  tv %>%
  mutate(rank = ifelse(avg_rating > 9, 1, 0)) %>%
  group_by(companies) %>%
  summarise(percent = sum(rank == 1) / n())

top 
top %>%
  filter(companies < 15) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = companies, y = percent)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

However, there are also disadvantages of the way multiple production companies works. To back up this alternative hypothesis, we created a table with a new rank of top, for tv shows with an average rating greater than 9. From our previous graph, we know that most tv shows have fewer than 10 companies involved. We then calculated the percentage of top tv shows for each possible number of involved companies. It is very clear that the percent of top tv shows produced by the collaborating companies decreases as the number of companies involved increases. The percent of top tv shows produced by a single company is larger than the percent of tv shows produced by multiple companies together. One is that the quality of a show may be affected. An independent TV show is usually low in reward, but its also low in risk. As a result, the guiding principle is the creation of quality work, with the hope that commercial and critical success will follow. But in the high-stakes game of millions of dollar investment, TV shows with multiple large production companies involved, the principal aim is return on investment, which means playing it as safe as possible (in both whats made and how its executed), appealing to the widest possible audience, and thus protecting everyones investment.
